Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
deleteModulePort(25.10)                                deleteModulePort(25.10)

Name
       deleteModulePort - Disconnects the specified port name from its net and
       deletes the port

Syntax
       deleteModulePort

       [-help]

       <moduleName>

       <portName>

       [-bus <startId:endId>]

       Disconnects  the specified port name from its net and deletes the port.
       Individual bits of a bus cannot be deleted.

Parameters
       -bus <startId:endId>
              Specifies the startId and the endId of the bus bit.

              Note:

              * When a bit port or bit net is connected to something else, the
                bit will notbe removed.

              * Bus bit ports to be deleted must be adjacent to each other and
                adjacent to either msb or lsb of the existing bus.

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each deleteModulePort.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man deleteModulePort

       <moduleName>
              Specifies the name of the hierarchical instance whose port is to
              be deleted.  Specify "-" for the top hierarchical instance.

       <portName>
              Specifies  the name of the port to be deleted. Wildcards are not
              supported.

Examples
              * The following command deletes port 'rst_i' from the top  hier-
                archical instance:

                deleteModulePort - rst_i

              *

                The  following  command  deletes  all  bits  of  the  bus port
                'data_i' of the hierarchical instance moduleB_inst:

                deleteModulePort moduleA_inst/moduleB_inst data_i

              *

                The following command deletes bus bits out[7], out[6], out[5],
                and out[4] from existing top-level bus port out[7:0]:

                 deleteModulePort - out -bus 7:4

Related Information
